Air France, Intesa Sanpaolo, Vinci, Zetes: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   V i c t o r i a   S t i l w e l l
-- 
2011-06-23T04:00:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-22/air-france-intesa-sanpaolo-vinci-zetes-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index slipped 0.6 percent to 268.07.
The Stoxx 50 Index dropped 0.6 percent to 2,525.49. The Euro
Stoxx 50 Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro,
fell 0.3 percent to 2,795.07.  Air France SA (AF FP): Mechanics at the French airline
began a rolling strike, the CGT labor union said. The shares
fell 1 percent to 10.43 euros.  Euronav NV (EURN)  : The Belgian oil-tanker owner obtained
a $750 million senior secured syndicated credit facility for six
years to refinance existing debt and said it will pay a margin
of 225 basis points more than the London interbank offered rate.
Euronav fell 0.9 percent to 9.31 euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA (ISP)  : Italy’s second biggest bank
said it raised 5 billion euros in a share sale as its capital
increase was fully subscribed. The shares rose 0.2 percent to
1.86 euros.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc (LSE)  : Europe’s largest
bourse by value of listed companies and TMX Group Inc. agreed to
pay special dividends of C$660 million ($678.9 million) in an
attempt to win support for their merger and thwart a rival bid
from Canadian banks and pension funds. LSE shares were unchanged
at 957.5 pence.  Prismaflex International (PRS)  SA: The billboard
designer and developer reported net earnings of 1.4 million
euros for the year ended March 31, up from a 0.35 million euros
loss a year earlier. The shares rose 2.5 percent to 12.89 euros.  Vinci SA (DG)  : Europe’s largest construction group said
it signed a contract to build a new headquarters for SFR, the
mobile telecommunications unit of Vivendi SA, in the Paris
suburb of St. Denis. The shares fell 1.4 percent to 42.51 euros.  Zetes Industries SA (ZTS)  : The maker of  Belgium ’s
electronic identity cards agreed to buy Johannesburg-based
ProScan for 5.2 million euros ($7.5 million) on a debt-free
basis and expects the transaction to contribute to earnings as
of July 1. Zetes Industries advanced 0.9 percent to 17.50 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Victoria Stilwell in New York at 
